			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I drafted this up after much dabbling because, frankly, Child of Ro pisses me off something awful. Frankly, I'm tired of one line of our pets getting the shaft, and having nothing to show for it. This pet in particular is of suprime disappointment as it is literally crap for a random turn in that you could get repeatedly, and couldn't sell for coppers if you tried, off a spectral parchment (which, for most, tend to be rather difficult things to get).
<br />

<br />
Anyways, soliciting opinions. Sending it off to SoE to see what kind of laughter I can start. Formatting gets to be fubar (yay, the wonders of html and msg boards).
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Dear Everquest Devs,
<br />

<br />
  To start off with, I would like to thank the fine people over at SoE to 
<br />
some of the improvements to the Magician class through the past few 
<br />
expansions. It does truely feel like we are capable of doing some serious
<br />
damage in the world. However, while our primary role, dealing damage, 
<br />
seems to be ok now, there are a few issues that I wanted to bring up, 
<br />
that were perhaps overlooked. Namely, what I'd like to discuss is the 
<br />
level 63 Fire Pet, and generally, all fire pets.
<br />

<br />
  To first ask, what exactally is the driving purpose for the Fire pet to
<br />
fill? Is it designed to be mitigation, utilizing stuns to repeatedly pin
<br />
down mobs and act as a pseudo-slow? Is it designed to be meerly a wizard
<br />
class pet, and deal out damage? Certainly, it is not meant to be a tank
<br />
pet, nor is it meant to do great damage in melee. It is usefull to know
<br />
what 'void' this pet is supposed to fill, to properly know how to tune it
<br />
into usefullness. My vision of this pet is to be a damage class pet (since
<br />
wizards themselves are also about damage) utilizing spell cast damage over
<br />
melee damage. It is this vision that I persue the topic on.
<br />

<br />
  The level 63 fire pet, spectral parchment gained, seems like a major
<br />
waste of a pet. In fact, most of the fire pets seem to have this problem as
<br />
soon as a magician hits level 50 and beyond. To illustrate, our pet goes
<br />
from a nice warrior pet with a fine damage shield and low hit points that
<br />
magicians have used to solo up to and including 50 to a wizard pet that has
<br />
use so situational that most do not summon it. The only variant that is
<br />
remotely usefull is a chain stunning pet, and that's only against casting
<br />
mobs that are easy to interrupt. Beyond that, his damage is negligable, his
<br />
tanking ability doesn't exist, and the AI that controls him is awful for
<br />
what kind of a pet he is.
<br />

<br />
  Now, I don't want to just rant and rave and bring up no actual details,
<br />
so I'm going to delve into some of the specifics of the problems. For the
<br />
52 fire pet, the standard spell lineup that it has is ok. It's not great,
<br />
but it's ok for that level. The 58 fire pet gets no upgrades to it's spell
<br />
lineup, even though it takes a jump in level from 44 to 49. The level 63
<br />
pet jumps 11 levels, yet STILL uses level 20 spells, some 1/3rd of it's own
<br />
level. In the planes, where these pets are to be used, that's horribly
<br />
outclassed.
<br />

<br />
  What use is a Shielding spell going to do a pet when it grants a whopping
<br />
50 hps? How about Shieldskin, which will absorb not even 1/5th of a single
<br />
hit from a planar mob? How about how usefull a chain stunning pet is going
<br />
to be against mobs that are immune to stuns from a level 20 wizard spell,
<br />
even though our level 61 Air pet can stun mobs that seem typically resistant
<br />
to such spells. And, to add misery to my testing, while the Burnout series
<br />
(versions 1-4) were adjusted to have the AC Component in effect slot 6, 
<br />
Burnout 5 (and Frenzied Burnout, and Ancient Burnout Blaze) will still 
<br />
overwrite the Fire pet's Shielding spell. At the least, consistency with the
<br />
Burnout spell effect line would be good.
<br />

<br />
  Some notable problems and solutions to them are illustrated below. While
<br />
such proposed solutions could take several directions, based on a Magician's
<br />
role as a damage dealer, I tend to recommend a specific path. To aid in the
<br />
discussion, a dictionary of terms used is located at the following URL:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/define.html" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/define.html</a>
<br />

<br />
1) Ditch the idea of a wizard class pet as unfeasable and revert the fire 
<br />
pet back to a melee class. Ranger with procs (not good choice), warrior 
<br />
(as it was pre-50), monk (not great, but feasable, though air tends to make
<br />
a better choice for this class). This option is the simplest viable option 
<br />
for us. It would give it some kind of use, but loses some versitility, and
<br />
adds redundancy where its not needed. If we need a melee pet, air is 
<br />
probably a better choice all around anyways. This is not a solution I would
<br />
hope to see come from any change.
<br />

<br />
2) Adjust the current 63 wizard pet to make it worth the effort to get.
<br />
Some proposed changes (spell and other):
<br />

<br />
 - Markar's Clash                 200hp DD, Stun 8.0sec        Wiz/49
<br />
 
<br />
    in place of Tishan's Clash (Wiz/20). Only contingency is that the stun
<br />
    has to be usefull on upper level mobs in the planes. If it is not, this
<br />
    spell change to the fire pet's lineup is almost as useless. Unlike our
<br />
    Air pet, who's AirElementalStrike has 'effective permission' to land on
<br />
    just about any and every level beast out there (given that it is not
<br />
    outright immune), Tishan's Clash does not. I don't believe Markar's
<br />
    Clash does either, but at least with this spell, the fire pet could
<br />
    actually do some damage with the spell, light though it might be.
<br />

<br />
 - Diamondskin                    394hp Rune                   Wiz/44
<br />
 
<br />
    in place of Shieldskin (Wiz/20). This would permit the fire pet to take
<br />
    a hit or two without major issue, but not boost the pet's ability to 
<br />
    tank significantly or tread far onto wizard toes. Alternatively, Steelskin
<br />
    (230hp Rune, Wiz/34) is more acceptable than Shieldskin.
<br />

<br />
 - Arch Shielding                 150hp, 27ac, 20mr            Wiz/44
<br />
 
<br />
    in place of Shielding (Wiz/16). Even if the pet's hitpoints have to be 
<br />
    adjusted to be balanced at least this would give the vision that the pet 
<br />
    was capable of casting spells more appropriate to it's level and having at
<br />
    least a less than trivial use.
<br />

<br />
 - Remove Instill from the spell lineup
<br />
 
<br />
    This particular spell makes the fire pet useless in cases where you want
<br />
    magic damage to be dealt. The pet will root and screw up aggro control much
<br />
    more than an earth pet would. At least with the earth pet, you know that 
<br />
    rooting is a part of what it is, and that it can sit there in melee and 
<br />
    take a beating. This firepet rooting, then engaging in melee only assures 
<br />
    that it will recieve a major beatdown at the hands of the mob, and with his
<br />
    meager hitpoints and lackluster shielding, he stands as much chance of 
<br />
    surviving as a tissue in a hurricane.
<br />
    
<br />
  -- Alternatively, change this spell to Bonds of Force (Wiz/29 AoE Snare). I 
<br />
     can't see as this would be likely to happen, but the AoE aspect of it 
<br />
     coupled with the high probability of the pet snaring itself make it a 
<br />
     possible risk/reward scenario. This proposal does counter a later one,
<br />
     but at least in this instance, mesmerization spells would not be broken
<br />
     due to the AoE.
<br />

<br />
 - Remove Cancel Magic from the spell lineup
<br />
 
<br />
    This particular spell, while the fire pets tend to do fairly good about 
<br />
    using it only when taking damage via a DS, has the potential to negate 
<br />
    any benefits you are trying to aid your party with through debuffs, snare,
<br />
    etc. Leave the decision on whether to dispell or not up to the caster, not
<br />
    the pet. Pets with dispell are different by far than Mobs with dispell.
<br />
    Pets must have a master with them, who can decide and aid them. A Mob must
<br />
    work it out on his own, and have the appropriate tools.
<br />

<br />
 - Remove the ability to cast AoE damage spells from the spell lineup
<br />
 
<br />
    While this use as a taunt is good, it becomes a major problem if the pet 
<br />
    AoE's and aggro's more creatures (normally non-aggro, experienced this 
<br />
    firsthand), or worse, breaks mez on mobs that are sitting nearby combat. 
<br />
    AoE'ing damage makes the pet a liability, and one that cannot be trusted 
<br />
    in combat situations such as that. Even the potential to AoE makes the 
<br />
    fire pet undesirable in cases where more than one mob will be present at
<br />
    any given time.
<br />

<br />
 - Replace Force Shock (Wiz/20), Garrison's Mighty Mana Shock (Wiz/20), and 
<br />
   Shock of Lightning (Wiz/12) with Lightning Shock (Wiz/39), Ice Shock 
<br />
   (Wiz/34) and Inferno Shock (Wiz/29).
<br />
   
<br />
    These spells are the main source of damage for the pet, as it's melee is 
<br />
    attrocious (it misses more than it hits, and with it's damage cap doesn't 
<br />
    put out respectable melee damage), these spells should contribute more to
<br />
    it's damage. I have also noticed a trend for our post-60 pets in that DPS 
<br />
    range goes from 50-70 for the Air pet in raw melee up to 100 for the water
<br />
    pet properly placed. I do not think it is unacceptable to expect the fire 
<br />
    pet to put out similar rates of damage in their given specialty, magic 
<br />
    damage, or at least a significant portion thereof.
<br />

<br />
    To note, however, I have yet to see the level 63 Fire pet actually use any
<br />
    direct damage spells in combat. He simply resorts to using Tishan's Clash
<br />
    and Instill. I also attempted to avoid tapping Lure spells or spells of
<br />
    unacceptably high damage given that these spells are generally balanced off
<br />
    of their recast, and NPC's typically avoid recast times when casting.
<br />

<br />
    URL's for parsed damage:
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/airpet.html" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/airpet.html</a> 
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/waterpet.html" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/waterpet.html</a>
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/firepet.html" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/firepet.html</a> (250kish, images)
<br />
    (No parse available for Rathe's Son)
<br />

<br />
    URL for raw log (250k per log):
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/air-raw.txt" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/air-raw.txt</a>
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/water-raw.txt" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/water-raw.txt</a>
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/fire-raw.txt" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/parses/fire-raw.txt</a>
<br />

<br />
 - Replace O'kell's Radiation with the innate Fire pet damage shield.
<br />

<br />
    One of the major balancing bits with the old fire pet was that their low hps
<br />
    was made up for by the fact that it could deal damage (sometimes significant)
<br />
    when a creature dared strike it. Based on the spell data for the Fire
<br />
    Elemental Aura, the 63 fire pet would wind up with a damage shield of 62
<br />
    points. I don't feel as this is unbalancing at all, as the fire pet still 
<br />
    cannot tank well, and such damage shields can already be achieved through 
<br />
    non-exploitive methods (Shaman potion, mage DS, bard sung DS). The pet will
<br />
    never see the potion or song improvements stacked onto his own DS to 
<br />
    increase it further. The Fire Elemental Aura is just like earth pets 
<br />
    rooting, an air pet stunning, and a water pet casting cold based spells. It
<br />
    simply is an innate ability of that elemental type. That got stripped away
<br />
    when it was classed as a wizard.
<br />
    
<br />
 - Change the Pet's AI to be a bit more consistent with it's role. Casting mobs 
<br />
   have not only higher hitpoints, but higher melee damage and far better 
<br />
   mitigation. The Fire pets are for non-melee situations. Their ability to 
<br />
   engage a mob in direct melee is atrocious.
<br />
   
<br />
  -- Alternative 1, use AI changes to let the pet avoid melee range and
<br />
     stay inside a 'casting range'. Of course, this poses the problem of a pet 
<br />
     getting aggro and fleeing, and the mob giving chase. This is not an
<br />
     ideal solution for anyone involved.
<br />
     
<br />
  -- Alternative 2, Once engaged, a fire pet rushes into casting range and
<br />
     then becomes "rooted" to it's spot while it has a mob on it's hate list 
<br />
     within casting range (though usually outside melee range). This prevents
<br />
     the pet from meleeing unless engaged directly in combat by the mob, but 
<br />
     will let the pet give chase if the mob flees from aggro range. This also
<br />
     prevents the pet from fleeing a mob, and provides a risk of the pet being
<br />
     killed should the pet be engaged in melee for the advantage of the pet 
<br />
     casting more often. With Instill removed from it's line up, this pet 
<br />
     would not be able to solo root/nuke a mob to death on it's own, making it
<br />
     still a situational, group-only pet.
<br />

<br />
  -- Alternative 3, improve the fire pet's max damage and melee skills. Even
<br />
     with improved spells, the balance between time spent casting, damage from
<br />
     casting, and damage from melee would be changed. The fire pet, spending
<br />
     likely twice as long spellcasting (average 2 sec previous, 4 second after)
<br />
     is going to improve his damage output slightly over double (179hp max nuke
<br />
     up to 403 hp, only some 2.25x improvement). With the pet already dealing
<br />
     less than acceptable damage on mobs of comperable level, the ability to
<br />
     melee sufficiently during 'Recovery Casting' and shorter windows of melee
<br />
     time during 'Normal Casting' would aid in the pet's usability.
<br />

<br />
 - Improve the size of the fire pet's mana pool and mana regen rate.
<br />

<br />
    Tests of the fire pet's capabilities show a lackluster mana pool from which
<br />
    to draw. Based on math (proof in following URL), a rough approximation of 
<br />
    the firepet's mana pool is ~2250 points with an approximate mana regen
<br />
    during combat of 6 mana/tick (proof below). While this seems sufficient for
<br />
    the spell set of Tishan's Clash and Instill, it would not survive long in
<br />
    combat utilizing higher damage spells. Here are some estimates of what a 
<br />
    fire pet could do with heavier spells. The "average recast" time is 
<br />
    garnered from a rough distribution of recast times from combined tests, a 
<br />
    'Chaincasting tendancy'. It's graph is below as well.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Code:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="code">
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 'Normal Casting' Estimate
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; Mana Pool&nbsp; Type of Spells&nbsp; Time to OOM&nbsp; DPS&nbsp; &nbsp; # of Casts
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2250&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;'Chain Cast'&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;129.6 sec&nbsp; &nbsp;37.66&nbsp; 12 casts
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2250&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;'Rotate Cast'&nbsp; &nbsp; 123 sec&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;31.58&nbsp; 4 rotations
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4000&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Chain Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;237.6 sec&nbsp; &nbsp;37.66&nbsp; 22 casts
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4000&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Rotate Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 246 sec&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;31.58&nbsp; 8 rotations
<br />

<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;'Recovery Casting' Estimate
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; Regen Rate&nbsp; Type of Spells&nbsp; Time to Recast*&nbsp; DPS
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 6 m/t&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Chain Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;185s &#40;3 min&#41;&nbsp; &nbsp; 2.18
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 6 m/t&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Rotate Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 493s &#40;~8 min&#41;&nbsp; &nbsp;1.96
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;20 m/t&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Chain Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;59s&nbsp; &#40;&lt;1 min&#41;&nbsp; &nbsp;6.83
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;20 m/t&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Rotate Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 155s &#40;2.5 min&#41;&nbsp; 6.26
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;40 m/t&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Chain Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;31s&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;13.0
<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;40 m/t&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Rotate Cast&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 96s&nbsp; &#40;1.5 min&#41;&nbsp; 10.1
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
     * Time to Recast for Rotate Cast refers to time to complete a full
<br />
       rotation. 3 casts total plus the time to regen the mana needed
<br />
       for all three.
<br />

<br />
    Basic Assumption:
<br />
      The fire pet takes on average 6 seconds to begin casting it's next
<br />
      spell. Least time to recast, 2 seconds. Highest, 22. DPS is always
<br />
      calculated by the formula:
<br />
        Damage / (cast time + average recast time) = DPS
<br />
   
<br />
    URL for proofs:
<br />
    <a href="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/graphics/manapool.jpg" target="_blank">http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/graphics/manapool.jpg</a> (150k)
<br />

<br />
  Hopefully, changes can be made to the current fire pet to make it a bit more
<br />
acceptable to use, and a bit more usefull. With the current unpredictability
<br />
and counterproductive behavior of the current incarnation, I see this pet
<br />
almost never in combat use, and I certainly do not use it myself. To me, this
<br />
is something that needs to be at least looked at and reviewed for possible
<br />
improvements, similar to what is being done about the Necromancer level 65 pet.
<br />
Magicians, while having 3 other suitable pets, are about the 4 elements. What
<br />
good is the class to have a sudden disreguard for one of it's primary callings?
<br />
Why would there be a sudden disreguard by the devs over one important aspect
<br />
of a class (Similar to discounting a warrior's tanking ability)?
<br />

<br />
  I hope this particular problem can be resolved one way or the other in order
<br />
to return this pet to some sort of usefullness.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Rhasin Firestorm
<br />
Arch Convoker
<br />
Prexus</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
