			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Ok, to illustrate my point about the fire pet's mana pool, I'm going to quote in a graph I had made.
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/graphics/firepet1.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Now, in this graph, the blue tick marks are when the pet began casting. During the first 5 and a half minutes, the pet cast reguarly, repeatedly, from anywhere between 2 second delay to 22 second delay between casts. After 5 minutes 30, the casting rate drops off mightily. In fact, of the 43 casts, all but 4 of them are done in the first 5:30 of the fight.
<br />

<br />
If it is caused by the AI, then it's seriously screwed up. There is no valid reason why a fire pet should slow down it's casting so greatly at that point in the fight. Also, there's something to consider in this second graph:
<br />

<br />
<img src="http://home.attbi.com/~c.wroten/graphics/firepet2.jpg" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
The time at which the pet stops casting in 'chain casting' mode is a little after 8 minutes, not 5:30 as previously. If it were the AI, shouldn't this time be approximately equal in all fights?
<br />

<br />
It is my belief that, while the fire pet is immune to mana sieves, it <span style="font-weight: bold">does</span> have a discernable mana pool. While I did not yet do math on the second graph to figure out a rough mana pool and approximate regen, an eyeball glance at it (since Instill and Tishan's Clash are both 60 mana to cast) the ammount of 'downtime' is much the same between the two fights (ie: the second run did not chain cast as much, so could extend it's casting 3 more minutes).
<br />

<br />
As for the BO5 bug, yes. I know. I mentioned it in the email, about 3-4 paragraphs in.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
